{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3c4b3e38-8c32-41ab-8282-545184f62f98","content":"The template has a solid foundation but has a few issues to address before publishing:\n\n**🔴 Functional bug:**\n- The `Framework` symbol has no `replaces` property, so the chosen target framework will never be substituted into generated `.csproj` files. Add `\"replaces\": \"net9.0\"` (or whatever placeholder is in your csproj).\n\n**🟡 Recommended for NuGet publishing:**\n- **Missing `$schema`** — add `\"$schema\": \"http://json.schemastore.org/template\"` for validation/editor support.\n- **Missing `groupIdentity`** — needed so multiple package versions of the same template coexist properly (e.g., `\"groupIdentity\": \"MyCompany.WebApi.CSharp\"`).\n- **Missing `preferNameDirectory`** — should be `true` for project templates.\n\n**🟢 Looks good:**\n- `identity`, `name`, `shortName`, `author`, `sourceName`, `classifications`, `tags` — all correctly set.\n\n**Verdict:** Not quite ready. The missing `replaces` on the `Framework` symbol means users can pick a framework but it won't take effect. Fix that and add the recommended fields before publishing.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"afb184ec-1b51-44fe-b700-9b5771554090","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Let me review this template.json for NuGet publishing readiness. I'll check against the .NET template engine schema requirements.\n\nIssues I can identify:\n\n1. **Missing `$schema`** — Not strictly required, but strongly recommended for validation and editor support.\n2. **Missing `groupIdentity`** — Recommended for NuGet publishing so multiple versions of the same template can coexist.\n3. **Missing `precedence`** — Related to groupIdentity, helps determine which template version takes priority.\n4. **Missing `preferNameDirectory`** — Minor, but commonly set for project templates.\n5. **`defaultValue` of `net9.0`** — This is fine.\n\n\n6. **Missing `replaces` property on the `Framework` symbol** — This is a real problem. The symbol is defined but won't actually substitute into the .csproj file, so the target framework won't change in generated projects. The `sourceName` is correctly set to `\"MyWebApi\"` for namespace replacement, but without the `replaces` mapping, the framework parameter becomes non-functional.\n\nLooking at the metadata structure, I'm also noticing several gaps that would matter for NuGet publishing: there's no `$schema` reference, no `groupIdentity` for versioning, and no `preferNameDirectory: true` setting. The most critical blocker is that missing `replaces` property — without it, the framework parameter is essentially decorative and won't actually modify the generated project.","outputTokens":779,"requestId":"401D:913B3:478AB6:53B689:69F005C0"},"id":"19f28692-d8d0-4385-a256-eac85fb94de8","timestamp":"2026-04-28T00:56:49.944Z","parentId":"3a84733c-e845-4656-af85-c0afa67d7f1f"}
